4.2. Robustness checks
This study employs the two-stage least squares (2SLS) instrumental variable method for estimation. Following Banker et al. (2019),
we use the average AIRatio of other banks within the same institution type and year (OtherAIRatio) as an instrumental variable for bank
AI adoption. The instrument satisfies the relevance condition, as banks of the same institutional type operate under similar regulatory
frameworks and operational constraints, which fosters peer learning incentives. Regarding the exclusion restriction, several factors
support its validity. First, AI diffusion effects operate primarily through knowledge spillovers rather than direct profit channels.
Second, for regional banks that constitute the vast majority of our sample, institutions of the same type typically operate in distinct
geographic markets, thereby limiting competitive effects on individual profitability. The results in Table 3 further confirm the validity
of OtherAIRatio as an instrumental variable. To address potential endogeneity concerns more comprehensively, we employ a lagged
independent variable approach (Appendix Table C) and implement the two-step system GMM estimator (Arellano and Bover, 1995;
Blundell and Bond, 1998) to address multiple endogeneity sources (Appendix Table D).
This study conducts three additional robustness checks. In Panel A of Table 4, the proportion of AI terms in the MD&A section of
