4.3. Mechanism analysis
This section explores the specific pathways through which AI adoption affects bank profitability, focusing on three mechanisms:
operating costs, income diversity, and mobile banking development.
To assess how AI adoption influences profitability through operating costs, this study employs the cost-to-income ratio (CostToIncome),
deposit interest expense ratio (DepositFundingCost), and demand deposits-to-assets ratio (DemDepositToAsset) as proxy
variables for bank operating costs. The results in Panel A of Table 5 show that AI adoption significantly reduces banks’ cost-to-income
ratio and deposit interest expense ratio, and increases the demand deposits-to-assets ratio. This indicates that AI adoption enhances
bank profitability by improving cost efficiency, reducing deposit funding costs, and increasing the share of low-cost funding.
To examine whether AI adoption affects bank profitability by broadening income sources, this study uses the non-interest income
ratio (NIIRatio), non-interest income to total assets ratio (NIIToAsset), and an income diversity index (IncomeDiversity) as proxy variables
for the degree of bank income diversity. The results in Panel B of Table 5 indicate that AI adoption helps increase banks’ non-
interest income and income diversity, thereby positively affecting profitability.
To analyze the role of AI adoption in developing mobile banking services, this study uses mobile banking app annual active users
(lnUsers), launch count (lnLaunches), and usage duration (lnDuration) as proxy variables for mobile banking development. The results in
Panel C of Table 5 show that AI adoption significantly promotes the development of mobile banking services and enhances bank
profitability through this channel.
We mitigate endogeneity via lagged regressors and 2SLS (using peer banks’ AI adoption as IV), confirming causal interpretations
across three channels.
In summary, the results of the mechanism analysis support research hypothesis H2.
