4.4. Heterogeneity analysis
This section explores the heterogeneity in the impact of AI adoption on bank profitability.
First, this study introduces a dummy variable for global systemically important banks (isGSIB) and its interaction term with AI
adoption. The results in Panel A of Table 6 indicate that the positive effect of AI adoption on the profitability of systemically important
banks is more pronounced. This heterogeneity stems from three theoretical mechanisms rooted in economies of scale and scope (Berger
and Humphrey, 1997). First, these banks can amortize AI infrastructure investments across larger customer bases and transaction
volumes, reducing unit costs. Second, their superior financial capacity enables investments in cutting-edge AI technologies and
specialized talent, facilitating sophisticated applications in credit risk assessment, fraud detection, and customer relationship management.
Third, their operational complexity creates greater optimization potential through AI-driven process automation and
enhanced decision-making, yielding proportionally larger efficiency gains.
Second, this study introduces a dummy variable for banks with high ownership concentration (isHighConcentration) and its
interaction term with AI adoption. The results in Panel B of Table 6 show that AI adoption has a more pronounced effect on improving
the profitability of banks with high ownership concentration. This finding aligns with agency theory and corporate governance
literature (Jensen and Meckling, 1976; Shleifer and Vishny, 1997). Concentrated ownership mitigates principal-agent conflicts and
information asymmetry, enabling decisive technology investment decisions. Major shareholders possess greater incentives and
monitoring capabilities to ensure AI expenditures target value-creating applications rather than managerial objectives. Additionally,
concentrated ownership accelerates consensus-building and implementation, enhancing integration with existing processes. This
governance efficiency enables superior resource allocation, rigorous performance monitoring, and stronger alignment between AI
capabilities and strategic priorities, thereby extracting greater value from AI investments.
Finally, this study introduces a dummy variable for banks located in regions with advanced FinTech (isHighFinTech) and its
interaction term with AI adoption. The results in Panel C of Table 6 show that for banks in regions with advanced FinTech, the positive
effect of AI adoption on profitability is more pronounced. This finding supports endogenous growth theory and innovation spillover
